var qsSteps = [{
  shortTitle: "What is CORAS",
  title: "What is CORAS",
  content: [{
    type: "text",
    content: "Have you ever asked yourself some of the following questions."
  }, {
    type: "unorderedList",
    list: ["Should I worry when using my credit card on the Internet?", "How safe is my Internet bank account?", "How many doctors or healthcare personnel have access to my personal health records?", "Can I be sure that I am the only one reading my e-mail?", "How crucial can a single personal mistake be for my company?"]
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "A security risk analysis may provide answers to such questions. CORAS is a method for conducting security risk analysis. CORAS provides a customised language for threat and risk modelling, and comes with detailed guidelines explaining how the language should be used to capture and model relevant information during the various stages of the security analysis. In this respect CORAS is model-based. The Unified Modelling Language (UML) is typically used to model the target of the analysis. For documenting intermediate results, and for presenting the overall conclusions we use special CORAS diagrams which are inspired by UML. The CORAS method provides a computerised tool designed to support documenting, maintaining and reporting analysis results through risk modelling."
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "In the CORAS method a security risk analysis is conducted in eight steps:"
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: _steps.default
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "We will go throught these steps in the rest of this tutorial"
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Preparation",
  title: "Preparation for Analysis",
  content: [{
    type: "text",
    content: "The first step is the initial\n                preparations for a risk analysis. The main objective is to\n                get a basic idea about what is to be the target and what\n                will be the size of the analysis such that we can make the\n                necessary preparations for the actual analysis tasks."
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/800/200"
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Customer presentation",
  title: "Customer presentation of the target description",
  content: [{
    type: "text",
    content: "The second step is the introductory\n                meeting with the customer on the behalf of which the\n                analysis is conducted. The main item on the agenda for\n                this meeting is to get the representatives of the customer\n                to present their overall goals of the analysis and the\n                target they wish to have analysed."
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/1000/500"
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "The objective is to\n                achieve a common initial understanding of the target of\n                analysis, and of what the parties of the analysis are most\n                concerned about. The overall goals of the analysis are put\n                forward, the focus and scope of the analysis are set, and\n                the rest of the analysis is planned."
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Refine",
  title: "Refine target description",
  content: [{
    type: "text",
    content: "The thirds step aims to ensure a common\n                understanding of the target of analysis, including its\n                focus, scope and main assets. The analysis team presents\n                their understanding of what they learned at the first\n                meeting and from studying documentation that has been made\n                available to them by the customer. Based on interaction\n                with the customer, the analysis team will also identify\n                the main assets to be protected."
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/750/300"
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "The analysis team\n                furthermore conducts a rough, high-level analysis to\n                identify major threat scenarios, vulnerabilities and\n                enterprise level risks that should be investigated\n                further. The outcome of Step 3 is a refined and more\n                detailed understanding of the target description and the\n                objectives of the analysis, which at this point are\n                documented by the analysts."
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Approval",
  title: "Approval of target description",
  content: [{
    type: "text",
    content: "The fourth step aims to ensure that the\n                background documentation for the rest of the analysis,\n                including the target, focus and scope is correct and\n                complete as seen by the customer. The step involves\n                presenting a more refined description of the target to be\n                analysed, including assumptions and preconditions being\n                made. Typically, the analysts describe the target using a\n                formal or semi-formal notation such as the UML. Before the\n                actual risk analysis starts at the next step of the\n                analysis process, the description of the target should be\n                approved by the customer. Step 4 furthermore includes\n                deciding the risk evaluation criteria for each asset. This\n                analysis step concludes the context establishment."
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/900/450"
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Risk identification",
  title: "Risk identification",
  content: [{
    type: "text",
    content: "The fifth step is the risk\n                identification. To identify risks, CORAS makes use of\n                structured brainstorming. Structured brainstorming is a\n                step-by-step walkthrough of the target of analysis and is\n                carried out as a workshop led by the analysts. The main\n                idea of structured brainstorming is that since the\n                workshop participants represent different competences,\n                backgrounds and interests, they will view the target from\n                different perspectives and consequently identify more, and\n                possibly other, risks than individuals or a more\n                homogeneous group would have managed."
  }, {
    type: "diagram",
    diagram: exampleDiagram2,
    width: 600,
    height: 300
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "The risk\n                identification involves a systematic identification of\n                threats, unwanted incidents, threat scenarios and\n                vulnerabilities with respect to the identified assets. The\n                activities are supported by the CORAS language, and the\n                results are documented on-the-fly by means of CORAS threat\n                diagrams."
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Risk estimation",
  title: "Risk estimation",
  content: [{
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/1000/75"
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "The sixth step aims to determine the\n                risk level of the risks that are represented by the\n                identified unwanted incidents. The unwanted incidents were\n                documented in threat diagrams during Step 5, and these\n                diagrams serve as the basis for the risk estimation. Step\n                6 is conducted as a brainstorming involving personnel with\n                various backgrounds, and basically involves the estimation\n                of the likelihoods and consequences of the unwanted\n                incidents. These values in combination yield the risk\n                level for each of the identified risks. The CORAS threat\n                diagrams facilitate the likelihood estimation by\n                supporting the estimation of the likelihood for threats\n                and threat scenarios to cause the unwanted incidents."
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Risk evaluation",
  title: "Risk evaluation",
  content: [{
    type: "text",
    content: "The seventh step aims to decide which\n                of the identified risks are acceptable, and which of the\n                risks must be further evaluated for possible\n                treatment. Whether or not the risks are acceptable is\n                determined by using the already defined risk evaluation\n                criteria and the results of the risk estimation. Step 7\n                furthermore involves estimating and evaluating risks with\n                respect to indirect assets."
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/450/200"
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/450/400"
  }]
}, {
  shortTitle: "Risk treatment",
  title: "Risk treatment",
  content: [{
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/g/700/400"
  }, {
    type: "text",
    content: "The eighth step is concerned with the\n                 identification and analysis of treatments. The risks that\n                 are found to be unacceptable are evaluated to find means\n                 to reduce them. A treatment should contribute to reduced\n                 likelihood and/or consequence of an unwanted\n                 incident. Since treatments can be costly, they are\n                 assessed with respect to their cost-benefit, before a\n                 final treatment plan is made."
  }, {
    type: "image",
    src: "https://placekitten.com/700/800"
  }]
}];
